## Summary

**Problem:** When using `JobChainingJobListener` together with `RefireImmediately = true` in a `JobExecutionException`, the chained follow-up job fires prematurely during every refire iteration. This happens because `JobWasExecuted` is called after each execution attempt — including failed ones that will refire — and it unconditionally triggers the next job in the chain.

**Root cause:** In `JobRunShell.Run()`, `NotifyJobListenersComplete` (which calls `JobChainingJobListener.JobWasExecuted`) is invoked in every iteration of the refire loop, not just on final completion.

**Fix:** Added a guard clause in `JobChainingJobListener.JobWasExecuted` (lines 94-99 of `src/Quartz/Listener/JobChainingJobListener.cs`) to skip chaining when the job is about to be re-fired:

```csharp
if (jobException is not null && jobException.RefireImmediately)
{
    return;
}
```

This ensures the chained job only fires when the source job has **definitively** completed (either successfully or with a non-refire exception). The `jobException` parameter already carries the `RefireImmediately` flag, providing all needed information.

**Verification:** All 1359 existing unit tests pass (0 failures, 5 pre-existing skips).

